N1  - ['Export Date: 26 May 2022', 'Correspondence Address: Carroll, W.K.; Department of Sociology, Canada; email: wcarroll@uvic.ca', 'Funding details: Alberta Ecotrust Foundation, AEF', 'Funding details: Nature Conservancy, TNC', 'Funding text\xa01:\xa0Our research questions required us first to identify the ENGOs and think tanks receiving significant financial support from Canadian foundations. We began with a request, in fall of 2018, to Revenue Canada for data on the 100 largest foundations in Canada (ranked by the total amounts of their gifts) and the 100 largest foundations (ranked by assets) – a total of 140 foundations, given the overlap between these lists. As part of the same request, we included eight additional foundations that a panel of knowledgeable researchers identified as being of interest to this research. The resulting data contained 18,346 records of donations in the donors’ 2017 fiscal year totalling CAN $1.377 billion, with a mean of $75,070 and a median of $5128. Each record indicated the donor, donee and amount given (as well as other attributes such as city of head office).', 'Funding text\xa02:\xa0The key exceptions to this pattern are themselves illuminating. Several social-ecological ENGOs receive funds from business-aligned foundations; however, these ENGOs do not pursue projects in tension with capital’s growth imperatives within Canada. The Weston Foundation funds both the Fraser Institute and Seed Change, a church-based project whose remit is primarily international (founded in 1945, this ENGO supports agro-ecological development internationally). The Calgary Foundation funds the Calgary-based All One Sky Foundation, whose social-ecological environmentalism focuses on building resilient communities in Alberta that will be able to cope with climate change (its website avoids any mention of the causes of climate change). The two bank-based foundations mostly fund conservation groups, but TD Friends of the Environment also supports Ecosource Mississauga, which promotes community gardening and other urban green initiatives that do not pose obvious challenges to business-as-usual. Halifax-based Ecology Action Centre, committed to ‘biodiversity protection, climate change and environmental justice’,11 is the only social-ecological ENGO receiving major funding from a foundation that also funds conservative think tanks (namely, the Donner Foundation).', 'Funding text\xa03:\xa0Within the network, the conservationist strain predominates. Fully 43 of the donees are of this type; 25 are social-ecological ENGOs; nine are clean growth ENGOs; 11 are think tanks; six are hubs. What makes this collection of organizations a connected network are the overlapping social circles of donors and donees. On one side of the relationship, several centrally positioned foundations make major donations to overlapping sets of ENGOs and think tanks (in decreasing order of centrality, Echo, RBC, Ivey, Schad, Sitka, Vancouver, Aurea, Weston, Suncor, Donnor, TD Friends). On the other side, the social circles of donees also overlap, as many of them receive donations from the same foundations. For instance, Tides (located at the centre) receives major funding from all of the six most central donors and from seven less central foundations. The Nature Conservancy (bottom centre) is funded by five of the relatively central donors and five less central ones. The social circles of Tides and Nature Conservancy overlap substantially, as both receive major donations from Echo, Schad, Sitka and the Vancouver Foundation.']
